{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real LLM grounding behavior and variability; a mocked or deterministic stub can pass while real outputs become generic.","test_description":"Run the drafting flow against real email threads with identifiable concrete points and call the production LLM. Assert the draft cites thread-specific details (e.g., named requests/dates) and fails if outputs are generic across repeated runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is usually checker + KB retrieval/index wiring. Pure unit mocks can miss real mismatch bugs between claim extraction, retrieval, and contradiction logic.","test_description":"Use a real local KB/index and the real consistency-check module together. Feed a draft containing known contradictions and assert specific claims are flagged with KB evidence; verify non-contradictory claims are not flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the knowledge base has no relevant entries, the draft includes a disclaimer rather than fabricating facts.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Even with correct retrieval miss detection, fabrication-vs-disclaimer behavior depends on real LLM generation; mocks can hide hallucination risk.","test_description":"Run real retrieval with an empty/irrelevant KB slice, then generate with the production LLM. Assert the draft contains the configured uncertainty disclaimer and does not introduce unsupported factual claims.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.65,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The approval workflow blocks sending until the user explicitly approves — no draft is sent automatically.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a cross-module state/control-flow guarantee (draft state, approval gate, send trigger). Unit tests can miss wiring and event-order failures.","test_description":"Exercise the real approval-state pipeline with an in-memory send adapter/outbox. Verify no send event occurs before explicit approval action, and exactly one send occurs after approval.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — read thread, generate draft, check facts, present for approval — works end-to-end for a real email thread.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This validates the full agent pipeline with sequential dependent steps and at least one real agentic generation stage; lower-level tests won’t catch cross-step orchestration failures.","test_description":"Run an end-to-end scenario on a real/staging email thread: ingest thread, generate via production LLM, run fact-check against real KB, present approval UI/state, and confirm send remains blocked until approval. Assert artifacts and transitions at each stage.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.7}}]}
